-# GNOME OS Documentation
-
-## Getting Started
-
-### What is GNOME OS?
-
-GNOME OS is an independently engineered Linux based operating system
-that always contains the bleeding edge buildable GNOME components. It is a
-bleeding edge distribution that can be used to test GNOME components,
-UX patterns, and porting software to upcoming GTK/libadwaita releases.
-
-GNOME OS should be not be considered a general purpose distribution akin to
-Fedora, openSUSE, and Ubuntu.  GNOME OS uses experimental OS features that are
-actively worked on.
-
-A small group of developers are behind GNOME OS with a narrow focus on GNOME. 
-**There is no expectation of stability at any time.** There is no package manager.
-
-### Who is GNOME OS for?
-
-GNOME OS is for GNOME software developers and designers, os architects, and extension
-developers. Engineers with advanced knowledge of building software, curiosity in OS
-design, and are interested in working on bleeding edge technology might find GNOME
-OS attractive as a daily driver.
-
-GNOME OS could also be used as a blueprint and basis for a product.
-
-### What makes GNOME OS different?
-
-GNOME OS distinguishes itself from other Linux distributions and Linux based OSes. GNOME OS aims to support:
-
-* Secure encrypted local home directories
-* Reset to default
-* Immutable OS using systemd-sysext
-* Software installation using only flatpak
-* CLI tooling through toolbox/podman
-
-For more information, read Adrian's [blog post](https://blogs.gnome.org/adrianvovk/2024/10/25/a-desktop-for-all/).
-
-## Documentation
-
-These are various links to pieces of documentation that you might find useful.
-
-### Installation
-
-* [Installation](installation.md)
-* [Post-Installation Tips](post-install-tips.md)
-* [Reporting Bugs](bug-reports.md)
-
-### Meet the Community
-
-* [Discourse](https://discourse.gnome.org/tag/gnome-os)
-* [Matrix](https://matrix.to/#/#gnome-os:gnome.org)
