-# Installing GNOME OS
-
-## Things to keep in mind
-
-### Hardware support
-
-GNOME OS does not guarantee hardware compatibility especially for new hardware. We have a [hardware compatibility list](https://pad.gnome.org/L6jFCDo8TiKpojF3eq8xBw?view#). If you run into problems with GNOME OS booting, please [file a bug](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-build-meta/-/issues/new) indicating the hardware and what component is failing.
-
-Please also try booting with the following kernel
-boot parameters:
-* remove quiet and splash
-* add earlycon=efifb video=efifb systemd.debug_shell=1 rd.systemd.debug_shell=1
-
-File bugs with the output of the boot for us to
-determine what has gone wrong.
-
-### Application support
-
-GNOME OS does not have packaging. That means that
-you will have to build software yourself to
-install it. Software installable by flatpak is
-possible. For CLI commands, you can use [Linux Homebrew](https://docs.brew.sh/Homebrew-on-Linux) 
-
-As well, you can also use [toolbx](https://docs.fedoraproject.org/en-US/fedora-silverblue/toolbox/) to install a container of your favorite distro and use software from there
-.
-
-## Installing GNOME OS
-
-
-### Prepare USB Drive
-
-The standard GNOME OS Nightly ISO can be installed and should just work on many computers, depending on how well the hardware components are supported by Linux. If you have Intel graphics and Wifi it's likely to work without problems. We are constantly trying to improve hardware support, so if you run into issues with your specific components, please report them here.
-
-* Download the latest [GNOME OS ISO](https://os.gnome.org/download/latest/live-x86_64.iso)
-* Plug in a USB drive and select it in GNOME Disks
-* In the ⋮ menu select Restore Disk Image..., open the ISO and click Start Restoring.... Warning: This erases all data on the USB drive.
-
-### Boot and install from USB
-
-In order to run GNOME OS you need UEFI to be enabled, and secure boot to be disabled.
-
-* Reboot into BIOS options and disable secure boot
-* Boot from the USB drive
-* Choose GNOME OS Nightly in the menu
-* Go through initial setup and create a user
-* If your destination disk contains data, erase it in GNOME Disks using Format disk... and selecting No Partitioning. Warning: This erases all data on the disk.
-* Upon logging in, a window will have proposed to install GNOME OS. Choose "Install now".
-* Select the disk to install to, and press Install
-* If the installer gives you a recovery key, your data is encrypted. Write the key down on a different device
-* You can then continue using GNOME OS
